{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523839"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:59:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:59:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13924"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13924"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.1,0.05,0.03,0.76]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6543"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114692"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6543"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13924"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96695"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4049"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13107"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43452"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48200"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114692"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of worsening fatigue and dyspnoea. She has a medical history of ischaemic stroke two years ago with good functional recovery, and heart failure with reduced ejection fraction. Her medications include aspirin, ramipril, and furosemide. She lives independently, regularly looks after her young grandchildren and describes watching them grow as a motivating factor in her life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears short of breath and fatigued. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 138/84 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She has bilateral pitting oedema to the knees and bibasal crackles on chest auscultation. Her breathing pattern alternates between periods of deep, rapid breaths and periods of shallow breathing or apnoea, consistent with Cheyne-Stokes respiration. Despite this abnormal breathing pattern, she remains alert and responsive when roused.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start beta-blocker therapy","Arrange for home oxygen therapy","Refer for hospice care","Commence morphine infusion","Commence intravenous furosemide"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of acute decompensated heart failure, including fatigue, dyspnoea, peripheral oedema, and bibasal crackles. The most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommence intravenous furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E to address the fluid overload. Intravenous diuresis will help reduce pulmonary congestion, improve oxygenation, and alleviate symptoms more rapidly than oral medication. A common starting dose for patients not usually taking diuretics and with normal renal function is 20\u201340mg intravenous bolus. A higher dose may be required in patients with renal impairment or those who are on regular oral furosemide, such as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s breathing pattern is consistent with Cheyne-Stokes respiration, which is characterised by alternating periods of hyperpnoea and apnoea. While Cheyne-Stokes respiration can be associated with end-stage heart failure, it is not always a sign of impending death, especially in patients with a history of stroke. In this case, given the patient\u0027s good functional baseline, desire to live longer, and acute presentation, active management of her heart failure is warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence morphine infusion\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate in a palliative care setting for symptom relief in end-stage heart failure. However, this patient\u0027s expressed wishes and functional status do not align with this approach at present. Moreover, while the patient is experiencing Cheyne-Stokes respiration, she is not described as being in severe distress. There are reversible factors (fluid overload) that can be addressed with diuresis, which may improve her symptoms without resorting to opioid medication. Morphine can worsen respiratory failure and should be reserved for situations where symptom control is critical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStart beta-blocker therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is an important part of long-term heart failure management, but it is not the most appropriate next step in the acute setting. Beta-blockers are typically initiated or uptitrated when the patient is euvolaemic and stable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange for home oxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered if the patient remains hypoxic after optimal medical management, but it is not the most urgent intervention at this time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer for hospice care\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature given the patient\u0027s potential for improvement with appropriate heart failure management and good functional status. While palliative care discussions around goals and limits of care are important in advanced heart failure, they should be initiated in the context of the patient\u0027s overall clinical picture and preferences. Palliative care input may also be needed if the patient remains symptomatic despite medical management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cheyne-Stokes respiration can occur in heart failure and is not always a sign of impending death, especially in patients with a history of stroke.","Intravenous diuresis is the most appropriate initial management for fluid overload in heart failure, even in the presence of Cheyne-Stokes respiration.","Palliative care options should be considered in the context of the patient\u0027s wishes and functional status, not solely based on the presence of Cheyne-Stokes breathing."],"references":["Brack T, Randerath W, Bloch KE. Cheyne-Stokes Respiration in Patients with Heart Failure: Prevalence, Causes, Consequences and Treatments. Respiration. 2011 Oct 18;83(2):165-76.","Atherton JJ, Sindone A, De Pasquale CG, Driscoll A, MacDonald PS, Hopper I, et al. National Heart Foundation of Australia and Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Guidelines for the Prevention, Detection, and Management of Heart Failure in Australia 2018. Heart, Lung and Circulation. 2018;27(10):1123-208. Available at: https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/for-professionals/heart-failure-clinical-guidelines"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96695"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13924"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96695"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T16:35:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T16:36:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"d